<seg id=1> Dole Calls on Common People to Pay Attention to Impotence in An Advertisement for Viagra Producer </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (Associated Press, New York, Telegram) Republican Dole, who ran for president in 1996, is launching a new movement. This time, he represents Pfizer Inc., manufacturer of the aphrodisiac Viagra currently sweeping the world, in an advertisement to call the attention of people to impotence.  </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> Dole will speak out in educational television advertisements with an emphasis on sexual impotence and general men's health.  </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> Pfizer is unwilling to disclose how much money it is paying Dole, and Dole will not mention the name of Viagra in the advertisement.  </seg>
<seg id=5> The advertisement will be aired early next year.  </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> Dole's advertisement marks the first time Pfizer has promoted Viagra via television.  </seg>
<seg id=7> Pfizer is considering whether or not it should launch any advertisement directly mentioning Viagra.  </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> In May, Dole admitted that he tried Viagra. He was profuse in his praise of the medicine, calling it a "magic drug." </seg>
<seg id=9> The 75-year-old Dole said in a statement: "I believe that the movement can help men pay attention to the health problems they fear to discuss." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=10> Since the appearance of this drug on the market in April, American doctors have written out over 6 million Viagra prescriptions.  </seg>
<seg id=11> There are 10-20 million men with impotence in the United States, and only 10% of them go to see doctors.  </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=12> Dole once went on a discussion program and advocated in Congress that his fellow countrymen be urged to get diagnosed and treated for prostate cancer early on as well as recognize a side effect of the treatment - impotence. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=13> Dole was diagnosed with prostate cancer in 1991. The doctor said that he recovered after undergoing an operation.  </seg>
</p>
